AllinOne

Target IP: 10.10.73.192

Scanning


According to the nmap scan, there are three TCP ports open on the target machine: FTP, SSH, and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

This FTP application allows anonymous login; however, there are no interesting files that I can access. Also, I do not have write permissions over it. Doing a Google search for vsftpd 3.0.3 does not show any public exploits.

Port 80: HTTP

The target machine is using a WordPress application at /wordpress directory. Apparently this box has multiple exploit paths.


Doing a WordPress scan with the command wpscan --url http://10.10.73.192/wordpress/ --plugins-detection aggressive, shows it is using the three plugins above.


The plugin mail-masta 1.0 is vulnerable to LFI. This exploit database page contains the PoC for the exploit.


After using the LFI exploit, I gained access to the /etc/passwd file. There is an interesting user called Elyana.


Doing a LFI fuzz with the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Fuzzing/LFI/LFI-gracefulsecurity-linux.txt -u http://10.10.73.192/wordpress/wp-content/plugins/mail-masta/inc/campaign/count_of_send.php?pl=FUZZ -fs 0 shows the interesting entry above. I did not find anything else important using this LFI.


And the content of this ssh_host_dsa_key.pub contains the content above. This key belongs to the user elyana. However, I was unable to login to the target machine using this key. Time to enumerate further.


Doing a directory search shows an interesting entry called /hackathons which contains the webpage above.


This directory /hackathons contains the HTML content above. It looks encrypted.


However, using the key KeepGoing I decoded the ciphertext to Try H@ckme@123. Time to spray the password H@ckme@123 against the username elyana I obtained from previous enumeration.

Exploitation


Spraying the credential elyana:H@ckme@123 against the WordPress application worked against the /wp-admin page.


Since the Theme Editor is enabled, I put the PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script inside the 404.php of Twenty Seventeen theme.


After updating the 404.php file of Twenty Seventeen theme, I started a listener on port 8443. To obtain a reverse shell connection on my local machine, I sent a curl request using the command curl http://10.10.73.192/wordpress/wp-content/themes/twentyseventeen/404.php to the target machine to activate the reverse shell. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as www-data.

Privilege Escalation


There is only one user called elyana at home directory. Spraying the password from WordPress did not work. However, apparently this user's password is hidden inside the system somewhere.


After some manual enumeration, I found the user's password. I used the command find / -writable -type f 2>/dev/null and found an interesting entry called /etc/mysql/conf.d/private.txt which contains the content above. Using the new password E@syR18ght, I was able to escalate my privileges to this elyana user on the target machine instead of www-data. This user is belongs to interesting groups.


Easy privilege escalation. It looks like the binary socat can be used with sudo. Then I spawned a new root shell.
